free_txt: Oak Ridge Electron Linear Accelerator
BIB corrections.
VM:Updated to new date formats,lower case.
NE-213 scintillation counter used to measure
incident neutron flux and secondary radiation from
sample. Small plastic scintillator located at edge of
beam used to normalize flux to cross section measure-
ments.
Largest source of systematic error is 10% absolute
uncertainty in flux measurement.
Oak Ridge Electron Linear Accelerator
Time of flight with 47.6-m flight path. Pulse
shape discrimination used to separate neutron from
gamma radiation. Backgrounds measured with empty
sample cans. Measurement of neutron flux taken
without sample or shadow bar in place.
327-g 7Li enriched to greater than 99.9%.
Encased in 0.005-cm stainless steel annular ring of
25-cm outer diameter and 15-cm inner diameter. Sample
thickness is 0.0867 atom/barn.
Data received on magnetic tape, G. Morgan,
Approved by G.L. Morgan, 1980/2/26.
Maximum correction of 10% for background. Also
corrected for average transmission of incident and
scattered neutrons, and multiple scattering.
Statistical uncertainty given.
Energy dependent error of 5% due to correction
in flux measurement.
Accuracy for transmission correction better than 3%.
Multiple scattering correction uncertainty is 10%.
Overall normalization uncertainty is approx 10%.
Electrons on tantalum filtered with 10-cm of
lithium and 11.4-cm depleted uranium.
Flux measurement made with additional 3.8-cm of
depleted uranium in filter to reduce gamma flash and
neutron count rate. Measurement corrected for this
attenuation using 7Li total cross sections.
Pulse height spectra integrated over intervals of
neutron time of flight to form specific neutron energy
range spectra. Spectra then converted to distributions
using computer code FERD and neutron response function
of detector.
Distributions normalized to cross sections using
neutron flux, average sample to detector thickness,
and sample thickness.
Maximum correction of 10% for background. Also
corrected for average transmission of incident and
scattered neutrons, and fraction of neutrons reaching
detector more than once.
Uncertainties do not include overall
normalization uncertainty of ~10%.

Accuracy for transmission correction better than 3%.
Multiple scattering correction uncertainty is 10%.
